{
  "guidedPractice": {
    "title": "Guided Practice: Checking Supply Pressure",
    "objective": "Guide the learner through selecting the correct instrument to measure electrical potential difference in an active circuit.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Scenario: You are investigating a motor that is running slowly. You need to check if the electrical 'push' or potential difference reaching the motor terminals matches the manufacturer's rating.",
      "Step 1: Identify the electrical quantity. To check the electrical pressure or potential difference, you must measure the Voltage.",
      "Step 2: Select the appropriate instrument. For measuring Voltage, the technically correct instrument is a Voltmeter.",
      "Step 3: Confirm circuit safety. Unlike resistance testing, this measurement is taken while the circuit is live and operational to see the actual supply level."
    ],
    "questionText": "Based on the steps above, name the specific instrument you must use to measure the potential difference across the motor terminals.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Voltmeter"
    ],
    "hint": "Think of the unit 'Volts'—the instrument name follows the same pattern as the Ammeter or Ohmmeter."
  },
  "practice": {
    "title": "Independent Practice: Measuring Work Rate",
    "objective": "Verify the learner can independently identify the correct instrument for measuring electrical power.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "In a commercial installation, a technician needs to determine the instantaneous rate at which a large heater is consuming energy. This 'rate of doing work' is a specific electrical quantity that requires a dedicated meter to measure both the pressure and the flow simultaneously."
    ],
    "questionText": "Identify the specific technical name of the instrument used to measure electrical power.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Wattmeter"
    ],
    "hint": "Power is measured in Watts. What is the name of the meter used to measure this quantity?"
  }
}

{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Integrative Close: System Diagnostic",
    "objective": "Synthesize the selection of instruments for static component testing versus long-term consumption monitoring in a practical scenario.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "In professional electrical work, you rarely use just one meter. A full system diagnostic often requires switching between instruments depending on whether the circuit is live or dead, and whether you are looking at a single moment in time or a long-term trend.",
      "Selecting the correct tool is not just about getting a number; it is about ensuring the measurement matches the specific physical property you are investigating, such as the physical state of a component versus the total work done by the system over a billing cycle."
    ],
    "questionText": "A client suspects their electric immersion heater is faulty and expensive to run. To investigate, you first isolate the circuit to check the physical condition of the heating element, and then you monitor the heater's total consumption over a full week. Identify the two specific instruments required for these two distinct tasks and explain why a Wattmeter would be the incorrect choice for the second task.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "The first instrument required is an Ohmmeter (to check the resistance of the isolated heating element).",
      "The second instrument required is an Energy Meter (or Kilowatt-hour meter) to monitor consumption over time.",
      "A Wattmeter is incorrect for the second task because it only measures instantaneous power (the rate of work at that moment), whereas an Energy Meter measures the cumulative energy used over a duration (Power x Time)."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about which meter requires a 'dead' circuit for a physical check, and the difference between measuring a 'rate' of use versus a 'total' amount used over a week."
  }
}

